Enclosing class:
JsHTMLElement
public static class JsHTMLElement.Member
extends DOM2HTML.HTMLElement.Prototype.Member

An opaque class representing members of its enclosing opaque type.

Note that, this class is opaque but its constructors are all internal. This class and the subclasses of this class are used to declare either opaque public instance fields of the opaque type Var.Member or the opaque public static fields of other opaque types while their constructors are used to define the fields inside opaque classes. Under either circumstance, the field names must be exactly same as the member names, as the opaque fields of opaque types are resolved by re-compilers directly based on the field names.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org
JavaScript:
Opaque types can be resolved but no class objects for them can be created in the target codes. Re-compilers must exit with error on operations accessing that kind of class objects. Re-compilers must resolve an opaque instance field declared by this class in Var.Member or its subclasses to the JavaScript identifier: 
q.m
where m is the identifier of the field name and q is the identifier resolved from the instance of the enclosing member. Re-compilers must resolve an opaque static field declared by this class in opaque types other than Var.Member and its subclasses to the JavaScript identifier: 
m
where m is the identifier of the field name. And re-compilers must report error on the access to opaque fields declared by this class under any other circumstances.

Field Detail

className

public final Value.String.Member className

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsHTMLElement object refers to the value of the class attribute of the element, which specifies zero or more space-separated CSS class names. Note that this property is not named "class" because that name is a reserved word in Java and JavaScript.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

innerHTML

public final Value.String.Member innerHTML

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsHTMLElement object refers to a read/write string that specifies the HTML text that is contained within the element, not including the opening and closing tags of the element itself. Querying this property returns the content of the element as a string of HTML text. Setting this property to a string of HTML text replaces the content of the element with the parsed representation of the HTML. You cannot set this property while the document is loading (see JsHTMLDocument.write(String) for this ability). This is a nonstandard property that originated in IE 4. It has been implemented by all modern browsers.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

scrollHeight

public final Value.Number.Member scrollHeight

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsHTMLElement object refers to the overall height, in pixels, of an element. When an element has scrollbars (because of the CSS overflow attribute, for example) the property differs from offsetHeight, which simply reports the height of the visible portion of the element. This is non-standard but well-supported property.

Since:
1.0

scrollLeft

public final Value.Number.Member scrollLeft

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsHTMLElement object refers to the number of pixels that have scrolled off the left edge of the element. The property is useful only for elements with scrollbars, such as elements with the CSS overflow attribute set to auto. This property is also defined on the <body> or <html> tag of the document (this is browser-dependent) and specifies the amount of scrolling for the document as a whole. Note that this property does not specify the amount of scrolling in an <iframe> tag. This is a non-standard but well-supported property.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

offsetParent

public final JsElement.Member offsetParent

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsHTMLElement object refers a node object specifying the container element that defines the coordinate system in which offsetLeft and offsetTop are measured. For most elements, offsetParent is the JsHTMLDocument object that contains them. However, if an element has a dynamically positioned container, the dynamically positioned element is the offsetParent. In some browsers, table cells are positioned relative to the row in which they are contained, rather than relative to the containing document. This is a nonstandard but well-supported property.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

onmouseover

public final JsFunction.Member<?> onmouseover

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsHTMLElement object is a reference to an event handler function invoked when the user moves the mouse over the element.

Since:
1.0
See Also:

Constructor Detail

JsHTMLElement.Member

public JsHTMLElement.Member(JsObject.Member q,
                            Var.Mid mid)

Internally constructs a member based on a qualifying member.

This constructor is internal and only called inside of opaque or internal classes or class members.

Note that, this constructor is internal but its declaring class is opaque. This constructor is used to define opaque instance fields declared in the declaring class of this constructor itself or its subclasses. Under this circumstance, the field names must be exactly same as the member names, as the opaque instance fields of the opaque type Var.Member or its subclasses are resolved by re-compilers directly to their names appending to the name resolved from the specified qualifying member with a dot in between.

Parameters:
q - A qualifying member
mid - The ID of the member to construct
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must report error on the invocation to an internal constructor.

JsHTMLElement.Member

public JsHTMLElement.Member(Var.Mid mid)

Internally constructs a member without a qualifying member.

This constructor is internal and only called inside of opaque or internal classes or class members.

Note that, this constructor is internal but its declaring class is opaque. This constructor is used to define opaque static fields, declared in opaque types other than the declaring class of this constructor itself and its subclasses. Under this circumstance, the field names must be exactly same as the member names, as the opaque static fields of opaque types are generally resolved by re-compilers directly to identifiers of their names.

Parameters:
mid - The ID of the member to construct
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must report error on the invocation to an internal constructor.
